rical and literary framework of which remains not yet fully mapped. Contributions from an international group of leading scholars from the field of Roman Literature and Rhetoric will explore the question of how Roman Declamation functions as a literary genre. This volume investigates the literary technique and the generic conventions of declamatio in its social, pedagocial and ethical context to determine “the poetics” of Roman Declamation. This volume is of interest to students and scholars of Rhetoric and Roman Literature. If you are interested in Roman Declamation, we also recommend the volume on the Declamations Ascribed to Quintilian by the same editors to you.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCalpurnius Flaccus. 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 0aRhetorik. 0aRoman declamation. 0aRömische Deklamation. 0arhetoric. 4aCalpurnius Flaccus. 4aRhetorik. 4aRömische Deklamation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aCalpurnius Flaccus.  aRoman declamation.  arhetoric.1 aBalbo, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasamento, Alfredo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinter, Martin T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinter, Martin T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuérin, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuérin, Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMannering, Jonathan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinho, Marcos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinho, Marcos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSantorelli, Biagio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.